    ## Literature Search Report: Dequantization, Quantum-Inspired, and Related Techniques (2023-2026)
    
    ### 1. DEQUANTIZATION OF QUANTUM ALGORITHMS
    
    **Core framework: Ewin Tang's sampling-based dequantization**
    
    The main body of dequantization work concerns converting quantum speedups for linear algebra / ML tasks into classical algorithms. The key insight: if data is stored in a structure supporting l2-norm sampling, classical algorithms can match quantum ones (up to polynomial factors) for low-rank matrices.
    
    Key papers:
    
    - **Bakshi & Tang, "An Improved Classical Singular Value Transformation for Quantum Machine Learning"** (SODA 2024, [arXiv:2303.01492](https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.01492)). Improves the classical SVT runtime from O~(d^22 ||A||_F^6 / eps^6) to O~(d^11 ||A||_F^4 / eps^2). This is the tightest dequantization of QSVT to date.
    
    - **Le Gall, "Robust Dequantization of the Quantum Singular Value Transformation and Quantum Machine Learning Algorithms"** (Computational Complexity vol. 34, 2025, [arXiv:2304.04932](https://arxiv.org/abs/2304.04932)). Generalizes dequantization to *approximate* l2-sampling access (not just exact). Applies to recommendation systems, supervised clustering, low-rank matrix inversion.
    
    - **"Towards Optimizing the Expected Performance of Sampling-Based Quantum-Inspired Algorithms"** (January 2025, [arXiv:2501.05184](https://arxiv.org/abs/2501.05184)). Optimizes two core subroutines: inner product estimation and sampling from linear combinations of vectors. Tightens measurement bounds for direct fidelity estimation.
    
    - **"On the quantum computational complexity of classical linear dynamics with geometrically local interactions: Dequantization and universality"** (May 2025, [arXiv:2505.10445](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.10445)). Shows polynomial-time classical simulation suffices for short-time dynamics of geometrically local classical linear systems -- no quantum advantage.
    
    - **"On Dequantization of Supervised Quantum Machine Learning via Random Fourier Features"** (May 2025, [arXiv:2505.15902](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.15902)). Provides conditions under which quantum neural networks and quantum kernels can be classically matched via Random Fourier Features.
    
    - **Tang received the 2025 Maryam Mirzakhani New Frontiers Prize** for this line of work.
    
    **Relevance to prime research:** The dequantization framework applies to low-rank matrix problems. The prime counting matrix pi_N has rank 2^{N/2-1}+2 (Session 17 result) -- exponentially high rank, not low-rank. The l2-sampling dequantization techniques do NOT apply to the prime counting problem because the relevant matrices are full-rank. **No pathway to polylog prime counting from this direction.**
    
    ---
    
