### The Key Reduction

The CRT framework (Proposal 2) identifies a **concrete reduction**: 

> **The entire O(polylog) p(n) problem reduces to computing p(n) mod q in O(polylog) for q ≤ 13.**

With M = 2×3×5×7×11×13 = 30030, CRT + R^{-1}(n) gives a **unique prime candidate** for all tested n. The blocking issue is that computing p(n) mod q currently requires pi(x; q, a), which costs O(x^{2/3}).

### Suggested Next Step
Deep-dive on whether the "prime race" pi(x;q,3) - pi(x;q,1) can be computed faster than pi(x) itself, possibly via structural properties of Dirichlet L-functions for small conductor q.

