    ## Overview of Chebyshev Bias and Prime Races
    
    Chebyshev's bias is the phenomenon that most of the time, there are more primes of the form 4k + 3 than of the form 4k + 1, up to the same limit. This is called the Chebyshev bias, or sometimes the prime race.
    
    ## The π(x;q,a) Function
    
    π(x; n, m) denotes the number of primes of the form nk + m up to x. More generally, for two invertible residue classes a and b modulo q, there exists a bias towards a (that is π(x; q, a) > π(x; q, b) is true more often than π(x; q, a) < π(x; q, b)) if and only if b is a quadratic residue and a is a non-quadratic residue.
    
    ## Recent Developments (2025-2026)
    
    Recent research has focused on new computational approaches and frameworks:
    
    As an application, results towards Chebyshev's bias have been obtained in the recently proposed framework of Aoki–Koyama (2023). Aoki and Koyama considered the weighted counting function πs(x; n, a) useful in the study of prime number races.
    
    A notable 2025 publication states that an explanation of the phenomena can be given only assuming the Generalised Riemann Hypothesis; previous work on the subject, such as the Rubinstein–Sarnak approach, also assume deep conjectures about the linear independence of zeros of the relevant L-functions.
    
    The search results don't contain specific information about computational complexity improvements in 2025-2026, but indicate active theoretical development in understanding the relationship between Chebyshev bias and L-function properties.
    
    
