    1	# Prime Research: Computing p(n) Exactly Without Bruteforcing
    2	
    3	## Goal
    4	Find an O(polylog) algorithm to compute the nth prime p(n) exactly.
    5	Target: p(10^100) in <1 second, 100% accurate.
    6	
    7	## Status (April 2026)
    8	- **560+ approaches tested** across 20 sessions, 145+ sub-agents
    9	- **All known paths closed** but no proof that polylog is impossible
    10	- **Problem is genuinely open** -- no unconditional lower bound beyond Omega(log x)
    11	- Best exact: `algorithms/v10_c_accelerated.py` -- O(p(n)^{2/3}), p(10^9) in 0.175s
    12	- Best approximate: R^{-1}(n) -- O(polylog), ~50% digits correct
    13	
    14	## The Barrier (One Paragraph)
    15	p(n) = SMOOTH(n) + RANDOM(n). The smooth part R^{-1}(n) is O(polylog) and gives
    16	~50% of digits. The remaining ~50% encode oscillatory contributions of ~10^48
    17	Riemann zeta zeros with GUE-random phases, information-theoretically incompressible.
    18	Best known: O(x^{2/3}) combinatorial, O(x^{1/2+epsilon}) analytic.
    19	
    20	## Where to Find Things
