CRT experiment result: **CRT approach is circular** — computing p(n) mod q requires π(x; q, a) which is as hard as π(x). The √x barrier applies equally to Dirichlet L-functions. Waiting for the remaining agents.


Probabilistic experiment: **All paths reduce to the same wall** — π(x) evaluation at a boundary. The adelic/CRT reconstruction needs surprisingly few moduli but computing p(n) mod p^k is equally hard. Waiting for more results.


Hierarchical sieve: **Phi recursion scales linearly with x** (ratio ~0.03-0.04 stays constant). Fourier spectrum of prime indicator is not sparse — 99% energy needs 78% of coefficients. Möbius sum sparsity doesn't scale. All three angles confirm the barrier.


Spectral compression results: **Zero sum needs far more than 50 terms** (residual 1.84 at x=10000). δ(n) is partially compressible — DCT captures 99% with 10% of coefficients — but the critical last 5% is dense in every basis. Fourier interpolation gives only ~2x savings. No path to polylog.

4 experiments done, 7 still running. Key pattern emerging: **every approach hits the same √x barrier from a different direction**. Let me check for the remaining results.


Dynamical experiment: **Prime gaps are unpredictable** (negative R² for all linear models). Prime indicator is **not k-automatic** (growing kernel, 38 vs 6 for Thue-Morse). p-adic structure is equidistributed as expected. No exploitable dynamical structure.

