**Experiment 1 (Candidate Generation) complete: CLOSED.**

Candidate set scales as O(sqrt(n)), not O(polylog). The RH-conditional error bound forces an interval of width O(sqrt(p(n)) * log(p(n))), containing O(sqrt(n)) primes. Filtering (mod 30, zeta zeros, small-prime sieve) gives multiplicative reduction but can't break the sqrt barrier.

4 experiments remaining...


**Experiment 4 (Pfaffian/Treewidth) complete: CLOSED.**

All three graph encodings have unbounded, polynomially-growing treewidth:
- Sieve graph: treewidth ~ x^0.36
- Lucy DP graph: treewidth ~ x^0.51 (worst — deeply non-planar)
- Prime dependency graph: **complete graph** for x ≥ 500, treewidth = #primes - 1

No FKT/bounded-treewidth shortcut exists. 3 experiments remaining...


**Experiment 2 (Class Field Splitting) complete: CLOSED.**

The information-theoretic setup works beautifully — 39 quadratic fields give 12.3 effective bits, enough for unique identification. But the **fatal circularity**: computing pi_split(x, d) requires either enumerating primes (circular) or using Dirichlet L-function zeros (MORE zeros than zeta alone). Cost is strictly WORSE than the direct approach.

2 experiments remaining (nilsystem + tropical)...


**Experiment 3 (Nilsystem Correlation) complete: CLOSED.**

Nilsequences are strictly worse than li^{-1}(n) — 0.84 correct digits vs 1.51. The dominant nilsequence modes are just sieve biases (1/2, 1/3, 1/5...). Green-Tao theory describes *collective statistics* (arithmetic progressions), not individual prime locations. Massive overfitting: R² drops from 0.56 (in-sample) to 0.25 (CV).

1 experiment remaining (tropical geometry)...
