    ## Recent Research on Approximate Degree
    
    Determining the approximate degree composition for Boolean functions remains a significant unsolved problem in Boolean function complexity, and researchers have concentrated on proving that approximate degree composes for special types of inner and outer functions. A 2025 paper shows that the approximate degree composes if either the outer function is a recursive function of the form h^d with d=Ω(log log n), or the inner function is a recursive function of the form h^d with h being any constant arity base function (other than AND and OR) and d=Ω(log log n).
    
    Additionally, a paper on torus polynomial approximations was accepted for ITCS 2026 with revisions completed in November 2025. This work develops machinery inspired by the method of dual polynomials to establish lower bounds on the degree of torus polynomials approximating Boolean functions, and applies this machinery to prove lower bounds on the degree of real polynomials approximating Boolean functions.
    
    The results indicate ongoing development in understanding approximate degree bounds through novel techniques like torus polynomials and recursive function composition methods.
    
    
