    1	# Modular Counting Attack: Results
    2	
    3	**Date:** 2026-04-05 (Session 28)
    4	**Experiment:** `experiments/circuit_complexity/modular_counting_attack.py`
    5	
    6	## Question
    7	
    8	Does decomposing pi(x) by residue class mod M (primorial) give SMALLER circuits
    9	for each per-class counting function pi_r(x)?
    10	
    11	This is distinct from CRT approaches (Sessions 3,7,9,13,20-22,24) -- we are asking
    12	about the circuit complexity of the COUNTING problem, not computing p(n) mod q.
    13	
    14	## Results Summary
    15	
    16	### Experiment 1: Mixed-Radix Conditional Entropy
    17	
    18	**Finding:** Conditioning on residue class DOES reduce entropy, but the reduction
    19	**SHRINKS as N grows** (for fixed M).
    20	
    21	| N bits | M=6    | M=30   | M=210  | M=2310 |
    22	|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    23	| 10     | 8.0%   | 14.1%  | 50.6%  | --     |
    24	| 12     | 6.3%   | 14.6%  | 24.0%  | --     |
    25	| 14     | 3.0%   | 12.8%  | 26.5%  | 52.2%  |
    26	| 16     | 1.1%   | 7.6%   | 25.9%  | 40.9%  |
    27	
    28	**Interpretation:** The entropy reduction comes from two sources:
    29	1. Removing small-prime divisibility (a constant contribution)
    30	2. Knowing the residue class (reduces uncertainty about local prime density)
    ... (120 more lines)
