    1	# Multiplicative Circuit Structure of pi(x) — Results
    2	
    3	**Session 28, April 2026**
    4	
    5	## Overview
    6	
    7	Explored the tension between MULTIPLICATIVE structure of primality tests
    8	and ADDITIVE structure of counting via three experiments.
    9	
    10	## Part 1: Legendre Sieve Inclusion-Exclusion Cancellation
    11	
    12	The Legendre sieve expresses pi(x) as a sum over 2^{pi(sqrt(x))} subsets.
    13	Each term is (-1)^|S| * floor(x / prod(S)).
    14	
    15	### Key findings:
    16	
    17	| x | subsets | distinct floor values | nonzero net | cancellation | fv/subsets ratio |
    18	|---|---------|----------------------|-------------|-------------|------------------|
    19	| 15 | 4 | 4 | 4 | 0.0% | 1.0000 |
    20	| 50 | 16 | 10 | 10 | 0.0% | 0.6250 |
    21	| 200 | 64 | 19 | 17 | 10.5% | 0.2969 |
    22	| 1000 | 2048 | 45 | 42 | 6.7% | 0.0220 |
    23	| 5000 | 524288 | 95 | 83 | 12.6% | 0.0002 |
    24	
    25	**Interpretation:**
    26	- The ratio distinct_floor_values / num_subsets drops rapidly — massive many-to-one mapping.
    27	- The floor value set has size ~O(sqrt(x)), matching the known bound |{floor(x/k)}| ~ 2*sqrt(x).
    28	- However, cancellation is WEAK: only ~10% of floor values have zero net contribution.
    29	- The remaining ~90% have nonzero net contribution, so the I-E sum cannot be simplified by grouping.
    30	
    ... (83 more lines)
