    {"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ef826ec6-72bc-452d-9992-0ae2ce68ddd2","agentId":"a67bee0b05072a325","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"You are testing a claim about prime number computation. The claim is:\n\n\"Verification that a candidate is p(n) costs only O(polylog(x)). The ENTIRE difficulty is in the prediction oracle.\"\n\nThe idea: if you have a guess g for p(n), you can verify it by:\n1. Check g is prime (AKS/Miller-Rabin: O(log^4 x) or O(log^2 x))\n2. Check pi(g) = n and pi(g-1) = n-1... but WAIT — computing pi(g) is the hard part!\n\nSo the claim needs scrutiny. Write and run a Python experiment:\n\n1. Given R^{-1}(n) as initial guess, what's the search range needed?\n   - Compute |p(n) - R^{-1}(n)| for n=100, 500, 1000, 2000, 5000, 10000\n   - Compute the prime gap at p(n) for these values\n\n2. KEY QUESTION: Can you verify p(n) = g WITHOUT computing pi(g)?\n   - You need to know g is the n-th prime, not just that g is prime\n   - Sieving the interval [g-gap, g+gap] and counting is O(gap * log(gap)) — how does gap scale?\n   - Gap ~ O(log^2(x)) under Cramer conjecture, O(x^{0.525}) unconditionally (Baker-Harman-Pintz)\n\n3. Compute: for each n, what's the cost of:\n   a) Primality test of candidate (polylog)\n   b) Counting primes in the search interval around R^{-1}(n) to identify which is the n-th\n   c) Total verification cost if the prediction is within k of the true value\n\n4. The REAL question: if prediction gives delta_hat with |delta_hat - delta| < D, what's the verification cost as a function of D?\n\nSave to experiments/proposals/critique_verification_separation.py and report results.\n\nWorking directory: /apps/aplikacijos/prime-research"},"uuid":"ecbcd010-66eb-48ed-af19-7d2e1e6e22ac","timestamp":"2026-04-05T10:38:07.562Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"31dce8f3-703c-42a8-8e9c-20c324520274","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"parti