    ['The experiment ran successfully. Here are the key findings:\n\n**The claim "Verification costs O(polylog)" is FALSE -- it\'s circular reasoning.**\n\nThe experiment saved to `/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/experiments/proposals/critique_verification_separation.py` demonstrates this in detail:\n\n**Part 1 -- Prediction error:** R^{-1}(n) gives errors of 0-55 at the tested range (n up to 10000). At n=10000, the error of ~40 spans about 3 prime gaps, meaning the search interval contains multiple prime candidates.\n\n**Part 2-4 -- The core problem:** Verifying g = p(n) requires TWO things:\n- (a) g is prime -- O(log^4 x), genuinely polylog, CHEAP\n- (b) g is the n-th prime -- requires pi(g) = n, which costs O(x^{2/3}), NOT polylog\n\nEven if you sieve a local interval to find all nearby primes, you still need to know the **rank** -- which one is the n-th overall. That requires computing pi(g-D), which is the same O(x^{2/3}) bottleneck.\n\n**Part 5 -- The circularity:** The only escape is if the oracle tells you the rank within the interval. But knowing the rank means knowing the oscillatory correction to O(1), which IS the original hard problem. The claim assumes its own conclusion.\n\n**Part 8 -- Scaling to the target:** At n = 10^100:\n- Primality test: ~10^9 operations (polylog, genuinely cheap)\n- Counting/verification (pi): ~10^68 operations (O(x^{2/3}))\n- The "cheap" claim is wrong by a factor of **10^59**\n\n**Bottom line:** Primality and ordinality are fundamentally different. Primality is polylog. Ordinality (knowing it\'s the n-th prime) requires counting, which is O(x^{2/3}) -- inseparable from the prediction problem itself. The "verification is cheap" framing conflates these two and is circular.']
