"
    Here is a concise report of the most relevant findings from 2024-2026, organized by topic:
    
    ---
    
    ## Literature Survey: Recent Advances (2024-2026)
    
    ### 1. Tensor Rank Methods for Circuit Complexity
    
    **Riffle Rank (Rossman, May 2025)**
    - Paper: "Riffle Rank," Benjamin Rossman (Duke), preprint May 2025
    - Introduces riffle rank: a complexity measure on even-order tensors. An n^k - o(log k) lower bound on riffle rank of the k-fold identity tensor would imply n^Omega(log k) lower bounds on arithmetic formula size for Iterated Matrix Multiplication, separating VNC^1 and VBP.
    - Relevance: new tensor-based route to algebraic circuit lower bounds; does NOT directly address Boolean p(n) computation.
    
    **Conditional Tensor Rank Lower Bounds (Chukhin, Kulikov, Mihajlin, Smirnova, ECCC TR25-038, April 2025)**
    - Under NSETH-style assumptions (Set Cover/TSP cannot be solved in 2^n), constructs explicit tensors with superlinear rank, monotone circuit size lower bounds, and matrix rigidity lower bounds.
    - Relevance: still conditional, not unconditional. Does not close or help the p(n) problem.
    
    **Tensor Factorizations and Circuits (arxiv 2409.07953, Sept 2024)**
    - Surveys relationship between tensor decompositions and arithmetic circuits. No new breakthrough lower bounds.
    
    ### 2. Slice Rank / Partition Rank
    
    **Slice Rank Survey (Cambridge Surveys in Combinatorics 2024)**
    - "The Slice Rank Polynomial Method -- A Survey a Few Years Later"
    - Covers state of art through ~2023; confirms slice rank remains a combinatorics tool (cap sets, sumfree sets) not yet connected to circuit lower bounds in Boolean settings.
    - Relevance: no new progress connecting slice/partition rank to circuit lower bounds for explicit number-theoretic functions.
    
    **Partition Rank and Partition Lattices (arxiv 2208.06932, updated 2024)**
    - Mostly combinatorics; no new application to circuits or p(n).
    
    ... (20 more lines)
